,Recommended,292180,11251285,"Posted: 15 July, 2014",all,FattyMooMooMan,"Have been waiting a while to buy this on steam (heard a bit back that it was supposed to be coming and I had played on an earlier version many years ago), very glad I bought it, not only is it a realistic simulator with a ton of control configuration options (it might all seem a little daunting at first, but persevere) but I am getting great pleasure out of learning to fly with Xplane...At the time of writing this review I have just done my first proper fight on Xplane 10 from Blackpool (EGNH) to Manchester (EGCC) - not a long flight (chose the route as these are local locations) but after earlier sims which basically gave you heading waypoints and large visual clues after clicking on a destination this was much more challenging. Used the VOR system to navigate to Manchester, during the flight Xplane taught me how several of the instruments worked that I glossed over playing previous flight simulators on PC.With my plane drifting a little to the left I had to correct my heading a few times (by a small amount) but eventually arrived at my destination. No clue how to use the local air traffic controllers (yet) I just picked a runway and landed...Learnt quite a bit from that hour playing the game and I can see it teaching me a lot more, I used to love flight-sims and played a lot but this game made me feel a complete novice again (especially after so long not playing any sims). However lack of arcade-game style assists, popup help and hand-holding made me feel like I really accomplished something in the game when I finally touched down. Been a while since I both enjoyed a game and felt like I achieved something.Worth the asking price? For me yes :)edit: I have added some comments to this review, including a very short version of how I used VOR to navigate, system specs and controllers being used."
76561197989698031,Recommended,292180,11235424,"Posted: 14 July, 2014",all,Snake_Pliskin,"Awesome. One of the few games I buy at full price without waiting for it to go on sale.This is a SIMULATOR. It is about as complex as what it simulates, flying an airplane. Expect there to be a learning curve. Expect it to be rather technical. Even for those of us who grew up on the MS flightsims (I started with MSFS 98), it can be a challenge.You WILL need a pretty hefty system to get the most out of this sim scenery-wise. The scenery itself can go from simplistic, just a few trees and buildings, to....realistic? heavily forested areas, congested traffic jams, city scapes, etc."
,Recommended,292180,16425478,"Posted: 15 June, 2015",all,GameroftheBeer,"This game is meant to be a full simulation of flight, and in no way is a simulation ""game"".  After this past weekend and around 10 hours playtime, probably only 5 which were spent in the sky,  I feel like I could legitimately fly a Cessna 172.  I honestly don't believe I would fly highly efficiently, but yes I could get off the ground and land.You NEED a controller or joystick to make the game reasonable in difficulty.  There are no tutorials so learning will be a lot of trial and error(hence the 5 hours on the runway).  I used an Xbox Controller, but don't bind acceleration to a thumbstick, bind it to A and B.  If it is bound to a thumbstick it will naturally rest in 50% throttle, you can fine tune thrust in small increments with keys.I do plan on buying a HOTAS setup(ideal), but they are pricey for good ones.  The graphics are decent and can easily be modded with free content downloads(100's) on the xplane forum to suit individual tastes.  Modding is easy, took me less than an hour to put in 4.  I will most likely replace more textures/meshes later for further realism.    This game will kill your harddrive space, especially when putting in UHD or HD texture meshes(google alpilotx), its free.The tons of freeware, mods, plugins, textures you find for this game easily double the worth of it.  Please not though there are no objectives, money, progression in this simulation.  IT is purely a SIM.  Travel time will be accurate as you fly, I spent an hour or more flying over Lake Michigan from Ohare to South Haven, MI in what has to be realistic travel time(Cessna 172).Don't buy this if you want a game, if you want to learn - buy this."
