76561197984324501,Recommended,292180,30945695,Posted: 4 April,all,xvii-Dietrich,"SummaryA true sand-box flight-sim, X-Plane 10 offers a huge variety of options for virtual pilots.Be warnedthat X-Plane 11 now exists, so you may wish to check that first, if you want the latest version. But version 10 is still a solid offering.Full reviewX-Plane 10 is a first rate flight sim. It isnotthe latest in the series, as X-Pane 11 has now been released. However I've really enjoyed using X-Plane 10 and this sim deserves a positive review. X-Plane 10 may also still be preferred for older machines.There is a modest selection of aircraft that come with it by default, some of which have high-levels of detail. However, it is the 3rd-party add-ons which are superb and which really add to it. There are hundreds of these (and thousands of community-built ones). If you are a serious simmer, you are probably already aware of this sort of thing, but for the novice, you should consider this as buying the ""sim engine"", rather than what you'll end up flying. That said, some of the default aircraft are still pretty neat. Many implement good flight models and superb avionics. The level of detail in some of the add-ons is breath-taking. Aircraft available range from the early days of aviation, through the war birds, early commercial airlines, small general aviation, spacecraft, modern fighter-jets, gliders, seaplanes and event remote-control models.The world is pretty much everything. Apart from the polar regions (over 80 deg latitude) every other continent is rendered. Compared to combat flight sims, the availability of nearly the entire planet is really quite something. Landscapes are pretty good, but there are loads of options for downloading open-source scenery packs, ranging from photo-rendered land-tiles to high-quality airports, complete with ground traffic, etc.From a multiplayer perspective, sites like VATSIM, IVAO, PilotEdge, etc. provide a way to fly with others online, including human air-traffic controllers. There are some single-player missions available for download, but for the most part, it should be treated as a simulator, not a game or mission. Also, as a flight sim, you would be advised to use a joystick. Even a basic one would give you a great start in learning to control the aircraft. In principle you can do it with the mouse, but it really is not so good.X-Plane 10 also comes with a utility called Plane Maker. This allows you to build or modify your own aircraft. As a result, there are literally thousands of community contributions. Some are a bit rough, but some are very professional, matching the quality of the paid add-ons. Additionally, there is a well defined network interface, making it possible to link other software to the sim or to add in your own hardware and controllers.So, in conclusion, if you are interested in flight, you will find X-Plane a great simulator environment. My only caveat is that now that X-Plane 11 is available, you should check that first!"
