76561198002311169,Recommended,292180,12250790,"Posted: 26 September, 2014",all,Amoun,"I thought I'd try out X-Plane 10 in the hopes that it would be able to replace the aging FSX. Whilst FSX is great and is the gold standard, it's old architecture places limits on it which we have pretty much reached now. X-Plane 10 is the ONLY 64bit high fidelity general  flight sim and that is able to fully use today's hardware. Add to that the fact that its flight model is more accurate out of the box than FSX and you have a recipe for success. Right?The flight model is good. The planes don't feel like they fly on rails (unlike stock FSX). The auto-gen scenery and effects are very good. The environment is gorgeous straight out of the box. It runs smooth as silk on my machine. But... I only put a few hours in the sim before regretting downloading it's 50 odd gig of content and returning to FSX. Why?Part of the joy of sims for me is immersion and level of fidelity to reality. Whilst X-Plane 10 hit the ball out of the park with flight modeling, its ""plausible world"" just simply isn't. I was dismayed to discover there are very few runways or airports with any buildings on them. Almost all of them are just flat strips on the ground with no buildings, no life, and no feeling of having actually arrived at a destination. Every landing feels like a landing on some remote bush strip in the middle of nowhere. In addition, the various cities and locations don't actually look much like those locations.  You have to go to great lengths with addons to rectify this sitation, and even then it falls short of the mark.The cockpits of the default aircraft look like they were made a decade ago (I think some were!) and a number of the 3d virtual cockpits just dont work at all. I was so disappointed that I felt the need to drop some money on a plane from Carenado on day one, just to enjoy the experience. This was a major disappointment.Another area that X-Plane get's let down on is developer support. Compared to FSX or Prepar3D, there is very little in the way of professional addons, scenery packs, and aircraft. X-Plane does have a thriving amateur community creating content... but that is exactly like it sounds.Oh, the UI is clunky as hell and the loading times are a nightmare!All that being said, I do enjoy the feeling of flight in X-Plane 10 and it does run very well. If you only care about flight modeling and the feeling of flight, and can live with scenery that doesn't reflect the real world then this is a great sim and I recommend it. If you are new to sims, it's Steam access makes it a great and easy place to start. It's for these reasons that I am going to give X-Plane 10 a thumbs up."
