,Recommended,292180,13884591,"Posted: 7 January, 2015",all,nickgovier,"I bought this because although I'm excited to see that Flight Sim X has been resurrected on Steam by Dovetail Games, it's still 8 years old, and I wanted to see how X-Plane has developed over the past 8 years.  I'm sure this is a good product, it sure looks very nice, but I wanted to flag a few things that new buyers should be aware of:1) X-Plane is the only 3D product I have ever used which isn't capable of changing the display resolution.  I'm running it on Windows 7 installed on a Retina MacBook Pro, which has a screen resolution of 2560x1600.  This is great for desktop work but awful for games, as that high a resolution on a mobile GPU means terrible performance.  This isn't an issue with any other game because you can set the resolution to 1280x720 to boost the performance and it still looks good on the 13"" screen.  However, if you set X-Plane to 1280x720, it draws that resolution in a tiny box in the middle of the 2560x1600 screen, which is basically useless.  If you want to run X-Plane at a lower resolution than your monitor, you need to change the Windows desktop resolution before loading X-Plane, which is a pain.2) Upon launching the game, I was parked on the end of a runway, ready to have a quick test flight to check out the graphics and performance.  However, it looks like there's no keyboard or mouse mapping for the flight stick - I was able to increase the throttles, adjust flaps, and get airborne, but there was no mapping for the aircraft flight controls!  Looking through the settings, I couldn't even see a mapping that I could change for these.  It turns out you can (technically) fly using the mouse - you have to click in the windshield of the 2D cockpit and you can then use the mouse to control the flight controls, but it's pretty nasty.  Also, this doesn't seem to work in 3D cockpit mode, which is my preferred view.3) To download the scenery, right-click on X-Plane in your Steam Library, and go to View Downloadable Content.  You can then click to download the other areas.  I was going to the X-Plane page in the Library, clicking on DLC on the right, which takes you to the DLC page on the Steam Store, where it was showing all the scenery packs as already in my library and ready to play, which was confusing (this is an issue with Steam's terrible user interface rather than X-Plane).I still recommend X-Plane, but you should be aware of the above issues if you're in a situation like myself."
