76561198161989289,Not Recommended,292180,20228071,"Posted: 2 January, 2016",all,cody.w.baker,"If you're both a Mac user and a flight simulator player like me then I'm sorry, you're screwed; X-plane is the only major platform flight sim for us, at least that I'm aware of. When I decided to uninstall Boot Camp et al for more drive space, I thought X-plane would be on par with MS Flight Simulator X. After all, most people in the sim community talk about the two games concurrently. And X-plane is very proud of how their aerodynamic models are better than those of FSX. Now, after +240 hours on X-plane, I can say that those aerodynamic models seem to have come at the cost of every other aspect of the game.Here's the good: most of the time, you can sync real world weather into the game. Also there is a good size community of free- and pay-ware DLC too. Finally, the flight models are great. A note on that last point, from where I'm sitting they are no better than FSX for the vast majority of flying.Here's the bad: the ATC is worse than useless. The game crashes often. The real weather updates every hour and every new map and the changes are immediate. The UI is a pain. And lastly there are errors in the weather radios.The ATC is breathtakingly bad. Here's the bottom line up front; you either file an IFR clearance or you don't use your radios at all. There is no in between. If you aren't on an IFR plan, there are no ground controllers, no towers, no traffic, nothing at all. It’s a radio wasteland for anything but weather. When you do want to file an IFR, the overwhelming majority of the time, I cannot get it to respond at all. I've looked up online help and searched the forums, but from where I like to fly out of (KUAO) they just do not respond. It’s a complete failure, and nothing ruins the immersion more than taking off at KLAX without talking to a single controller.The weather sync is interesting and fun, but it makes the game more unstable. It also makes flying more interesting than it needs to be. When I said, “the changes are immediate,” I meant one second the wind is 030@13 and the next moment, it’s at 240@30. It makes things very interesting indeed. I've had it go from sunny to stormy in as long as it took to read this sentence. And the manual weather UI is, along with a lot of other points in the UI, useless. Random weather? Okay but it'll be 20 degrees C most of the time. Want to see where your plane is on the world map? Okay but click anywhere on the globe and poof, your transported there, oh and at the same altitude. My An-24 (a really well done payware machine I really recommend) responds badly to being transported into the inside of a mountain. Finally, I know at least some of the AWOS channels are wrong, for example KAST gives you the weather for Olympia, WA, which is not near to the airport.In summary, the X-plane people seemed to have focused on only one part of making a flight simulator: the flight. And it's great, it really is, however, it comes at the expense of everything else in the game. It’s hard to enjoy the flight dynamics when you're on final at KSFO with silent radios and a cross wind that just changed 180 degrees in less than a second. I think comparing X-plane to FSX is like comparing a super car and a sports car for a daily driver, let's say the Porsche 911 GT2 RS to a Porsche 911 Carrera. Both are great cars; fast, fun, and exciting. The first can do +200mph. But the second has air conditioning and a radio. Which do you think you'll use more?"
