76561197974688776,Recommended,292180,11316845,"Posted: 19 July, 2014",all,terrorpapst,"I've been flying X-Plane since version 7 and spent countless hours in the virtual cockpit of this simulator. I'm very please to see it on steam now, so that we don't have to carry 8+ DVDs anymore.X-Plane 10 is what it says on the tin. An extremely realistic flight simulator. I comes with a complete high-res world scenery package and a descent collection of standard aircraft out of the box. Yet it's not a game that takes your hand and tells you what to do. It's a flight simulator that requires some commitment to get the most out of it. You'll literally learn how to fly along the way.Like with other flight simulators the real power lays in modification. There are tons of free custom airport sceneries out on the web, many of which are quite stunning. The same goes for planes. For a long time free resources dominated X-Plane, yet in recent years high quality payware Add-Ons of stunning quality emerged, so that even the most pampered Flight Simulator use finds very well made airliners, photorealistic sceneries and so on.My setup consists of hundreds of custom airports, dozens of payware aircraft (mostly airliners) and a small array of tools like PFPX to do the flight planning. With that I conquer the world almost daily. For long flights I often chose the Flightfactor Boeing 777 while shorter hops are a lot of fun using one of Peters Aircraft A320 or A321 models. Looking for a realistic A380? No problem, there's one. More of a Boeing guy? Go forthe 747-8i then. Not into airliners at all? Have fun with the KingAir 200 or a Cessna Corvalis TT. Why not a Challenger 300 business jet for a change. Oh and there's the occasional flighter trip you can do for thrills at supersonic speeds. Too slow? Take the space shuttle for a few circles around the earth.My point here is that X-Plane 10 is what you make of it. It's an open world, literally, that allows you to fly as close to the real thing as you can get.It doesn't blow the budget on hardware (I run it with rather high setting on 500$ hardware!), yet doesn't have any limits to what it can take hardware wise as well. So whatever you throw at it, it will only look better.The weather engine is quite detailed. Weather may be generated at random, drawn out on a map or finetuned. Want the real weather? Just download it and don't forget to check your weather radar (yes there's one!)After years of using X-Plane I never grew tired of it. If you're looking for a modern, realistic, extendable and smooth running flight simulator, X-Plane is a great choice and I can only recommend it. If you're unsure, check out the official website for the free demo. Check out the community, which provides a lot of useful information and creates new resources, most of them free, on a daily basis.See you in the skies!"
